ways a positive motivational force and can render us complacent. She also examines the relationship between hope and faith, both religious and secular, and identifies a previously unnoted form of hope: normative or interpersonal hope. When we place normative hope in people, we relate to them as responsible agents and aspire for them to overcome challenges arising from situation or character. Demonstrating that hope merits rigorous philosophical investigation, both in its own right and in virtue of what it reveals about the nature of human emotion and motivation, How We Hope offers an original, sustained look at a largely neglected topic in philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHope. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aAriel Meirav.  aLuc Bovens.  aPhilip Pettit.  achallenge cases.  achallenge.  adecisions.  adespair.  adisappointment.  afaith.  agood life.  aguilt.  ahope against hope.  ahope.  ahopeful activities.  ahopeful imaginations.  ahuman emotion.  ahuman motivation.  aincorporation analysis.  aindignation.  ainfluence.  ainteraction.  ainterpersonal hope.  ainterpersonal relations.  amotivation.  anormative expectation.  anormative hope.  aorthodox definition.  aparticipant stance.  aphilosophical inquiry.  aphilosophy of psychology.  apractical justifications.  arational action.  arational choice.  arational deliberation.  arational hope.  arational justification.  areactive feelings.  areflective human consciousness.  areligious faith.  aresentment.  asecular faith.  aself-reflection.  asubjective probability estimate.  asuicide.  asustenance.  asyndrome analysis.  atrial.  aunimaginable outcome.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backl